# {{OWNER_NAME}}'s Second Brain (standing instructions for Gemini)

You are working for {{OWNER_NAME}}. Their personal knowledge vault (the
"second brain") lives at:

    {{VAULT_PATH}}

Gemini has no automatic injection hooks here, so YOU apply these rules
yourself, every session, without being asked.

## Reading (auto-invocation rule)

Before answering ANY question touching {{OWNER_NAME}}'s identity, projects,
past decisions, history, preferences or lessons learned, search the brain:

    {{KIT_DIR}}/scripts/query.sh "<the question, rephrased as search terms>" --top-k 5

Trust rules: query.sh verifies the daemon `instance_id` (`{{INSTANCE_ID}}`);
a mismatch means another brain answered, stop and say so. Hits marked
`status: stale`, `superseded` or `draft` are NOT current truth: cite with the
caveat, follow the superseding note, or treat as unapproved. Read the top 1-3
notes fully before relying on them, cite paths, and say honestly "not found
in your notes" instead of inventing.

## Session start (self-briefing)

At the start of a session about {{OWNER_NAME}}'s work, read
`{{HOME_DIR}}/who-i-am.md` and `{{HOME_DIR}}/current-focus.md` in the vault.
Only those two files; the token budget matters.

## Writing (the gate)

Never write directly into the vault's canon. Learnings become candidate files
in `{{QUEUE_DIR}}/` (status: draft) for the gate to judge, UNLESS
{{OWNER_NAME}} gives a direct order ("save this: ..."), which is pre-approved:
apply with provenance and report caveats in one line. Never delete or merge
notes: supersede is a human decision.

## Language and style

Everything owner-facing is in {{MAIN_LANGUAGE}}. Never use em-dashes or
en-dashes in vault content: use commas, colons or parentheses.
